  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.12006" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>Sept. 4/89.<lb/> Prof. Dr. Schuchardt</dateline>
        <opener> Dear Sir:</opener>
        <p> Thanks for the copy of your article on "English Creole".<note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Es handelt sich wohl um <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.659">Schuchardt (1889 [= HSA 221])</ref>
            </bibl>. In der Bibliothek Brintons ist offenbar auch ein Exemplar des Texts vorhanden (<bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.3033">Weeks 2002: 333</ref>

            </bibl>, fälschlicherweise unter dem Titel des Artikels, der direkt vor Schuchardts Text in der Zeitschrift 
<hi
              rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
Englische Studien</hi>
 zu finden ist).</note> I take great interest in such studies, &amp; have examined it with much pleasure. Some day you will doubtless give us a philosophic appreciation of what should be understood by linguistic disintegration. Is it not evolution? </p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yrs tly</salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1203">
D.G.Brinton.</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
      <div corresp="#L.12006" subtype="original" type="appendix" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
        <p>Personal. </p>
        <p>Dr. Daniel G. Brinton, Editor of the 
Medical and Surgical Reporter, at Philadelphia, has been elected "Professor of Ethnology and Archæology," in the 
Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia. Dr. Brinton has made numerous contributions to ethnological literature, especially in relation to the linguistics, mythology, ancient history and archæology of the native races of America. He is Vice-President of the 
International Congress of Americanists, and a member of numerous learned societies. The Professors of the Academy deliver a course of lectures annually on their respective branches, and have charge of the museum and collections.</p>
      </div>
    </body>
